Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment:
I watched Mr Rogers on television as a small child. Later in life I simply remember it as "The show with the traffic lights". I have vague memories of noticing the differences between early and later episodes, I loved the idea that the trolley ran through his house. 
He died when I was 3-4 years old. I never knew he died until many years later, I see the show referenced on YouTube, and a substitute teacher walked in singing the theme once. 
It was eerie to watch episodes online and have the vaguest memories of who he is. 
I would love to remember a specific episode to look for, but I was too young for any of them to leave a lasting impression beyond anything repetitive.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment: When I grew up, I heard Fred Rogers in an interview say he was inspired to start his program because he was looking for something to watch with his own children, and came across programming where people threw pies at one another and didn't get along with each other. I knew right away the shows he was talking about. I'm in the first generation of kids that benefited from the influence of Mr. Rogers. When I was a preschooler, we had some horrible kids' shows -- not really suitable for kids, and I knew it. Sure, there was the Friendly Giant, and Captain Kangaroo, and Romper Room -- those were gentle and peaceful. But there were others that were nothing more than burlesque and slapstick. They were marketed as kids' shows, but they tossed out adult "jokes" that were supposed to go over our heads. Maybe it was supposed to get the parents to watch, but it made my parents change the channel in embarrassment.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment: I am going to see this film in Toronto in a few weeks with my husband and a friend of mine who recently lost her husband. I get emotional and start crying just watching the trailer because I have so many memories watching Mr. Rogers as a child. I actually felt like I knew him even though I'd never met him (obviously lol) and that he was actually my friend. Words can't describe how inconsolable I was when he died. I only had a vague understanding of what it meant to die at that time (thanks in large part to his show), but all I knew was that it was permanent and I wouldn't be able to watch his show anymore. This is one of those "famous" deaths that still stings every time I am reminded of it. I truly have no idea how I am going to make it through this documentary if the trailer has me crying this much. But that was one of the great things about Fred Rogers--he encouraged people to express their emotions rather than shying away from them and for that, I will always be grateful to him.

Comment: I am going to see this tonight.  I can tell from this trailer that this documentary will be one of those rare moments in life when I will be so inspired that it will change me as a person.  I'm 42, and of course, growing up in the U.S. how could I forget Mr. Rogers Neighborhood?  As a kid the show did not appeal to me at all.  I think I was old enough when it was on t.v. that it seemed like a show that was targeted more for very young children.  I just wanted to watch G.I. Joe or Thundercats or Transformers.  Now that I'm all grown up, this man inspires me like very few people have.  These are fearful times in the world of today.  Increasing temperatures around the globe.  Politicians with no moral compass whatsoever.  A country polarized and divided.  People are angry and afraid.  Hatred consumes us.  It consumes me.  This is exactly what I needed to see right now.  Folks, here is the undeniable truth that we can learn from this man and the wonderful legacy he left us:  If we can all take a good hard look at ourselves and see the anger inside of us, the fear, the hatred of those whose views threaten our own, and find within ourselves kindness, warmth, empathy, compassion, love - for the love of humanity, we can change the WORLD!!  And I for one have every intention of keeping the lessons this man gave us deep within me and starting by looking at the man in the mirror.

Comment: I saw the film a week ago, &  just watching this trailer the tears start welling up again..why? Watching this reminds us his message is still alive, and each of us can spread it, even if it's only in our own family, or neighborhood.  Mr. Rogers would want us to hope.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment:
I think the reason why this trailer gets to so many of us adults is...  first off, many of us hadn't seen this show in decades.  So now, with this trailer, we hear the voice...the music...we see the images.  It brings us back to a time when we were carefree.... innocent... safe and taken care of by our parents.

Cut to today's world, where we live in a 24/7 news cycle full of gloom and doom, not just about our own towns and cities, but other states, other countries...the entire planet.  I firmly believe that 24/7 access to 'news' (and let's face it, most of the 'news' we hear is bad/negative) is extremely bad for our psyche.  We humans were not designed to ingest so much constant bad news.  It affects how we view the world.  It affects our day-to-day lives...our moods...our outlooks for the future.

We've also lost our connections to our families....to our neighbors...to our communities.  Especially in the bigger cities, everyone is in a rush....everything is 'scheduled', even when it comes to the lives of children.  Children can't just 'be' anymore.  Their helicopter parents want their kids to 'succeed'...to be 'the best they can be'.  Their are in after-school classes.... multiple sporting teams.... taking martial arts classes...dance....music, etc.  Even 'play dates' are put on the calendar.

Whatever happened to kids just running through a field of UNmowed grass full of dandelions and grasshoppers (instead of being told by their parents to 'avoid' walking on their perfectly manicured lawn, which is instead full of pesticides versus dandelions and grasshoppers)?  

Whatever happened to kids playing ball outside, or going for a bike ride (instead of sitting like a zombie, glued to their glowing device... or else being carted to and from the neighborhood school by SUV, instead of walking five minutes to school)?

Why are adults afraid to make that first step and say 'hello' to a neighbor...to introduce themselves... to bring them a homemade pie or a bunch of flowers?  Why do so many people believe 'well....people just don't do that anymore....people keep to themselves nowawadays...if I were to do that, they might think I'm weird...'  Says WHO?!  

We all need to start making changes in our world, and it starts with us...the man in the mirror.  I happen to live in a big city (NYC) and.... we all know the stereotypes of life in NYC.  People believe that it's 'normal' in apartment buildings, to be anonymous... to just say 'hi' to folks you pass by in the hallway, and that's it.  People often (incorrectly) believe that people just want to be 'left alone'.  Well somewhere there is a happy medium between being an aloof neighbor and being a busy-body pain-in-the-butt neighbor.  Many people, particularly in big cities like NYC, are YEARNING for more connections to their neighborhood...to their neighbors.  But far too many people are simply 'chicken' to take that first step.  But not me.  ;-)

I live in a small apt building (just 8 units) and have dubbed myself 'the Julie McCoy' (i.e., Cruise Director on the show, Love Boat) of my apt bldg.  I am always very friendly to my neighbors.  When new folks move in, I leave them flowers with a 'welcome' note.  I host occasional parties and invite folks in the bldg.  I grow fresh herbs on my balcony and then offer them up to neighbors, etc.  And....it has paid-off, in the form of casual 'friendships' developing in the building, and mainly Thanks to Me! ;-)  Sure, not everyone in the building has necessarily 'responded' to my efforts.  Some clearly prefer to keep to themselves.  And it's like 'ok....I get it...you don't seem interested, so I'll leave you alone'.  But for the others in the building, we've developed a very casual 'network', whereby every now and then we might get together for a drink at a local bar.  Other times if one of us is travelling, we will offer up produce from our apartments that we won't be able to eat in time before our travel.  Or we will ask a neighbor to water our balcony plants while we are out of town.  And so on.

It all starts with US.  Let's all try to be a bit more like Mr. Rogers.  In doing so, we then give others 'permission' to do the same...that 'no', we won't necessarily all think them 'weird' for being friendly or neighborly.  ;-)

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment:
Mr Rogers has always been there - all my life. I wasn't a HUGE watcher, except when young. But the knowledge he was there - for everyone, has always been comforting in some way throughout my life. Like a constant, whether I was a rapt child; sullen, dismissive teenager; "on the go, too busy" 20-30 something, and now parent. I admit, I do feel guilty for the times in my sullen, angry teenage years when I dismissed Mr Rogers as corny or wimpy. Because I knew deep down he was none of those things, and that regardless of my behaviour....he'd wait until I came around to kindness. He'd always be there. 
I've had a happy life, and it's been made more so in a general way by Mr Rogers exemplar of how to see the world and treat others.

He showed how to be by constant gentle example, not insistence. 

And as the film demonstrates, his feelings, philosophy and approach to child psychology and education was quietly profound. A kind of relentless persistence of kindness. And what do you know? THAT turns out to be the most powerful approach. 

The neighbourhood is also deeply nostalgic. Although he embraced demonstrating new technologies, the neighbourhood is slow, considered, free of the distraction of modern electronic communications devices....except an old dial up phone; and somehow innocent, incisive and deep with important messages at the same time.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment: I saw this documentary last night in the theatre and I highly recommend it.  It is probably hard to believe but Fred Rogers was very much the same person he portrayed on his show.  His intentions were pure and good and he truly wanted children to understand their self worth while teaching them how to live in the real world of childhood.  His show dealt with issues of race, death, assassination, anger, and the difficult topics.  Fred Rogers never b.s.ed his child audience.  And this documentary does not b.s. its audience.  It covers all areas of Rogers' life including rumors about him being gay, accusations of teaching kids to feel entitled, self-doubts, depression, and his early lack of comfort with LGBT issues which he came to accept later.  We Presbyterians do not canonize Saints, but if we did, Fred Rogers would be most worthy of this status.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment:
Fred Rogers was the most Christ-like person I knew of. Nothing but pure and tangible love exuded from him. From the moment changed into his sweater to when he said "I'll see ya next time.", it seemed the world was at peace. I miss him so much. I'm crying as I write this. I'm a grown man. But everytime I see Mr. Rogers and hear his voice I cry out of sadness because he's not with us, and out of joy because he reminds me and so many others that we are perfect the way we are. Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment:
One of my cousin's worked on the set of Mr Rogers Neighborhood in the mid 70's, and he did say that Mr. Roger's was, on the street, just as you saw him on the set. This show was his "ministry" and to his credit, he knew how to tackle those really tough subject's like Death, and Assassination. I think you can sum him up in his own words at 1:22 "Love is at the root of everything....All Learning, All Relationship's.........Love, or the Lack of it".
I think one of the crowning moments of his life ( apart from his TV show, of course ), was his testimony to the Senate in 1969, to fight against the loss of 10 million dollars to PBS......  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fKy7ljRr0AA  You can see what kind of person he was only 1 year after his show first went on the air......before everybody knew who he was.

Comment: Man... The Winnie The Pooh trailer made me happy and nostalgic, but not cry. This, though... I sobbed buckets. He was such a massive part of my childhood in the 80s. Made me feel so special and loved, even when I was bullied daily. It's quite a contrast when you're told you're unworthy and stupid, yet come home to such a genuine, loving man who tells you the exact opposite. I honestly wish I'd taken his words to heart over the negativity. I miss this man so much! ;_; I remember wanting to give him the biggest hug. Too bad I never met him. If he were alive today, I can imagine how many of us would be lining up to offer our gratitude. I will definitely see this with a box of tissue in-hand. <3 Love you, Mr. Rogers!

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment: Unfortunately, I didn't appreciate him as much as should have while his show was on.  I grew up in a family where expressions of feelings were ignored or punished, so I learned to tamp them down deep.  As a result, I couldn't understand Mr. Rogers' message.  Years later, I shed a tear when he passed, but didn't realize the angel that we lost.  Now, at 44, FINALLY, I get it.  My family (ie - my *very* mentally ill parents) was the problem, not him or his show.  I left all that pain behind, and now I watch his show as an adult, and I'm learning, now, what I missed out on as a child.  I desperately miss his compassion, his strength of purpose, his unconditional love for all.  What I wouldn't give to have just a few minutes of his time (tearing up as I type), to tell him how much he means to me, and how much he's helped me heal the deep wounds of childhood.  And I'd ask for his advice on how to be a better person.  I wonder what he'd tell me.  And wherever he is now, I really hope I get to meet him someday.

Comment: I was reading some stuff on him on Wikipedia. I saw this section where it said he loved an SNL sketch satirizing him and thought it was funny. But then later on a Burger King ad did a parody of him, and he got furious. It wasn't that he was mad that they were making fun of him, but rather that the ad was clearly aimed at young, impressionable children who might not tell the difference between the commercial and the real him. The SNL spoof, on the other hand, was late-night programming that was clearly aimed at an older audience. So what i got from that, was that he had a good sense of humor and was perfectly okay with people poking fun at him, as long as the children didn't get involved. I like that.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment: It's a sad reality with how our generations have changed through moral decay. Those from my generation were able to take Fred Roger's intrinsic message from his show and understand it was with pure intent. We saw him as a television father and someone we could trust when he comforted us on issues that were too extreme when we were kids.  Unfortunately the same cannot be said about kids from this generation who see this great man and can't help but see him as "creepy", "gay" or an "undercover pedophile".  Perhaps that is the residual reality that is left once innocence and purity has been stripped away over time from dark reality. Although my generation had its scandals and violence too but the majority of us maintained a mutual respect, understanding and love towards one another and I believe television hosts as Mr. Rogers played a small role in that. A show like his would never take off,  not in this day and age. Too may selfish people.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment:
Fred Rodgers was one of those rare and most amazing and inspiring people in human history. I can't even express how humbled and honored I feel that I was born and raised during his initial influence on public television. He was a gift and a blessing. 

In conversation, people have often wondered and questioned me on how I could possibly feel that while growing up during the 70's and 80's, for myself and numerous school fellows, how it was that many of us held great respect and appreciate for the beauty of diverse cultures and yet never bought into the mindset of racism. 

Some think it may have been the area I was raised or the fact that my extended family has many races throughout it's make up, including Black, White, Asian and Latino. And still others don't believe me when I make such claims and label me delusional or a fraud. Well, the first two may personally have had something to do with it, but what helped to reinforce this understanding in myself and as for my varying school fellows the answer is very clear... shows like Mr. Rodger's Neighborhood, Romper Room, Sesame Street and The Muppet Show. I am forever grateful for the great and humane influences of my childhood like Jim Henson, Frank Oz, Joan Ganz Cooney, Lloyd Morrisett, Sally Claster Gelbard, Fred Rogers and the odd card in the bunch, Carl Sagan.

How anyone on Earth could actually down vote anything involving Fred Rogers is beyond me. They might need to take some time and visit the old neighborhood that Mr. Rogers loved so much. I certainly hope they do.

One of my favorite interviews with Fred Rogers:
https://youtu.be/XKjKZKpEkVY

Comment: Reverend Fred Rogers was successful for the same reason his imitators fail: he treated small children like people. He didn't talk down, he addressed concerns of childhood as things worth addressing and taking seriously and trusted that children could handle tough subjects if you were willing to take the time. Maybe most of all, he didn't play a character. What you saw on the Neighborhood was what you got. Seriously, go watch his testimony before the Senate about public television and tell me that's not the same guy that walked onto a TV set, sang and put on a sweater and sneakers every day for decades.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment: I know everyone feels like they HAVE to like Mr. Rogers, but I never liked his show.  I'm sure he was a very kind man who meant well, but I could never get past the fact, (even as a child) that he was such a nerd, and was SO old fashioned, with that nasally voice and looked like a televangelist, who I disliked immensely and didn't trust.  I hated how he would leave his house at the end of the episode too, and it always left me with a fear of abandonment.  Why did he leave, and where did he go?!?  I NEVER understood this!  It always gave me the creeps knowing that when the sun went down, his house would slowly get dark, and no one would be there, and I wondered where he slept at night?  Such a cold and lonely feeling.  I also was very influenced by puppetry, and his puppets mouths didn't open and close like the Sesame Street puppets, so I could never identify with them.  I LOVED Sesame Street and was inspired by Jim Henson's puppets, and liked the cast of real people better.  They, and the show were just cooler and more innovative.  I know he must have meant a great deal to a lot of kids, especially in homes where there was no love, or even abuse, but what he offered I was already getting at home from my parents...

Comment:
"Knowing that we can be loved exactly as we are gives us all the best opportunity for growing into the healthiest of people." 
--Fred Rogers

Whenever a celebrity or well-known individual passes away, a common phrase is, "The world is a little less ______ without him/her in it." For Nelson Mandela, the word was "bright". For Robin Williams, the word was "funny". For Fred Rogers, the word was "neighborly", but it wasn't just a nod to his television show. Every time I think of this man, I cry. I look at the changes in the world since February 27, 2003 and the changes in how we relate and interact with each other, and I grow incredibly sad. He was the personification of social consciousness. When he died, his message went with him, unfortunately for us.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment: When I was a kid, Mr Rogers was my hero. I think for many children, he held this position of perfect trust and comfort. Every time the show would end each day, I would cry. My mom would have to take me into my room and make me take a nap. This continued as long as I can recall while my family still lived in Temple City, California, a suburb of Los Angeles near Pasadena. We moved when I was 11, so it's very likely I continued to cry when his show ended up until that age. I don't remember crying about it at our new home. I'm not sure at what age I stopped crying at the end of his show, but I do remember that I did it for a long time. Fast forward 22 years to 2003. I was watching the news and I heard the news report that Mr Rogers had died. I started crying hysterically. I guess the final curtain closed and the show ended forever, and the last and loudest cry was wailed. I went back to my room, got in bed and fell asleep. I will never forget that moment. Whenever I pray to God and I need comfort or advice, I hear the voice of Mr Rogers in my ear, and his spirit comforts me. This may seem weird, but it really happens, and it helps me out quite a bit. I'm not talking to the dead. Their spirits are alive and are with God. If God permits it, their spirits can contact us if we are willing to listen. They use the same method God uses to talk with us. They will speak to us, but we have to be willing to listen and have faith that they are real. Are you a believer and listener?

But when Mr Rogers came on I would get so happy. Because he felt like a parent that I never had. He showed me my worth, when others kicked me down. Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment: Mister Rogers RUINED MY LIFE. (Click here for incontrovertible proof: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCjB-TDoEXHI59cWk-VHcENQ ) Having spent my formative years both living in Pittsburgh and being brainwashed by his gentle, well spoken manner and pianistically charged propaganda into thinking that it would be very nice if people were thoughtful and kind to one another, this impressionable nerd could not help but grow up to be helplessly and tragically civilized. And as if that were not interesting enough, once, whilst walking past a church in a Pittsburgh neighborhood known as "Squirrel Hill" (a place frequented by many squirrels), I happened to see Mr. Rogers stepping around the corner on his way into the church. And he noticed that I was noticing him. And do you know what he did? He gave me a friendly wave and said "Good morning!" And, without using any special effects, he even made his voice sound uncannily just like it sounded on television. It was like "good MORNing!" So I said "good morning" back to him - only I pronounced it "GOOD morning" because I didn't want him to think that I was being cheekily impolite. Okay, so now I can't even be mean to telemarketers. Besides, most of them seem like rather nice people once you get to know them. I am doomed...

Comment: Mr. R had a theory that (not just for children but even for adults) staring at an emoting face on a tv or movie screen brought them back to staring at "the mother's face" in early infancy, during bonding. That was why every episode would have times where you'd just get a relatively close shot of his face, staring very directly at you and talking calmly to you with love and acceptance. He was trying to provide that same kind of unique and deeply enriching, positive emotional experience, especially for kids who hadnt had enough. He wad an Incredible person.

Comment:
One of the most amazing things is how the show reached multiple generations of children. There are the children who watched when the show first came out. There was the endless reruns up until PBS finally stopped showing it during the day. And then there is Daniel Tiger's Neighborhood that's airing right now. I've just turned twenty and I remember watch Mr. Roger's Neighborhood when I was little. I'm pretty sure my mother watched it when she was little too. And every time I babysit kids, they will watch it as well. No matter how many times I've heard Mr. Rogers sing "Won't You Be My Neighbor?" it still brings me back to sitting in my living room and feeling that no matter how i acted or who I was, Mr. Rogers cared about me.

Title: WON'T YOU BE MY NEIGHBOR? - Official Trailer [HD] - In Select Theaters June 8
Comment:
I was born in 1970 and Mr Rogers always gave me a sense of peace in my unstable childhood . Well I am 48 now , and can say there is no other like him . I lived and still do about 25 minutes from where he grew up ( Latrobe PA ). I watched him on WQED . My boss has a son with autism and she told me that in the 1990s they were able to arrange a special tour of the WQED studio and sets for him with Mr Rogers himself . My boss said that she was unexpectedly starstruck , and Mr Rogers was lovely . Another interesting thing my boss told me  is that her aunt who has since passed , went to high school with Fred Rogers and that aunt said that he was exactly like you see him on TV . Same calm sweet personality . Fred Rogers mother's maiden name was McFeely and he had a sister named Elaine , sound familiar ? If you ever get the chance , go to Idlewild Park in Ligonier . For years they had "Mr Rogers neighborhood of Make Believe" where you could ride the trolley https://www.idlewild.com/things-to-do/attractions/mister-rogers-neighborhood . Now that he is gone it is "Daniel Tiger‚Äôs Neighborhood" , The trolley runs along the same track that ushered park guests through the former Mister Rogers‚Äô Neighborhood of Make-Believe ride, which operated at the park from 1989 through 2013. 
He really got it , the statement that " love or the lack thereof is at the root of everything "  gave me goosebumps . We all need to strive to be more like him .
